did.abstract: Groups of photographs that document contemporary photographers, as well as individuals related to the study of photography, 1982-2007; street photography in the San Francisco Bay Area, circa 1981-2009; sites throughout the American West, 1982-2008; and portraits and views, 1982-2017.

acqinfo.head: Immediate Source of Acquisition
acqinfo.p: The bulk of the collection was purchased from Abraham Aronow on the Frederick W. and Carrie S. Beinecke Fund for Western Americana, 2011.
Series III. Scenes from the American West, as well as Series IV. Portraits Acquired in 2012, are gifts of Abraham Aronow, 2012.
Series V. Portraits and Views Acquired in 2017, is a gift of Abraham Aronow, 2017.

accessrestrict.head: Conditions Governing Access
accessrestrict.p: The materials are open for research.

userestrict.head: Conditions Governing Use
userestrict.p: The Abraham Aronow Photographs is the physical property of the Beinecke Rare Book and Manuscript Library, Yale University. Literary rights, including copyright, belong to the authors or their legal heirs and assigns. For further information, consult the appropriate curator.

prefercite.head: Preferred Citation
prefercite.p: Abraham Aronow Photographs. Yale Collection of Western Americana, Beinecke Rare Book and Manuscript Library.

processinfo.head: Processing Information
processinfo.p: Collections are processed to a variety of levels, depending on the work necessary to make them usable, their perceived research value, the availability of staff, competing priorities, and whether or not further accruals are expected. The library attempts to provide a basic level of preservation and access for all collections, and does more extensive processing of higher priority collections as time and resources permit.
Titles and descriptions of individual photographic prints derive from lists provided by Aronow.

bioghist.head: Abraham Aronow (born 1940)
bioghist.p: Abraham Aronow is a photographer and retired medical doctor. He chiefly focuses his photographic work on portraiture of photographers, artists, authors, musicians, scholars, scientists, physicians, and other people he admires.

Aronow was born in Brooklyn, New York, and raised in New Haven, Connecticut. He received his Bachelor of Science degree at Massachusetts Institute of Technology and his Doctor of Medicine degree at Harvard Medical School. After medical school, Aronow served as an intern at Bellevue Hospital in New York City, and as a commissioned officer in the United States Public Health Service. Since 1969, he and his wife, Alice Barney Aronow (born 1942), a clinical social worker, have lived in San Francisco, California. Aronow retired from medicine in 2007.

At ten years old, Aronow learned photography from his father, an amateur photographer. In 1981, while working at Ralph K. Davies Medical Center in San Francisco, landscape photographer Ansel Adams became one of his patients. Adams invited Aronow to a filming session attended by the surviving members of Group f/64 and other photographers. This began a decades-long project by Aronow to make portraits of prominent photographers and other figures.

scopecontent.head: Scope and Contents
scopecontent.p: Groups of photographs that document contemporary photographers, as well as individuals related to the study of photography, 1982-2007; street photography in the San Francisco Bay Area, circa 1981-2009; and portraits of individuals involved in the arts, letters, and sciences, as well as views in the American West, 1982-2017.

Each folder in the collection contains a single black and white photographic print or ink jet print, except where color photographic prints and/or two or more photographic print or inkjet prints are noted.

arrangement.head: Arrangement
arrangement.p: Organized into five series: I. Portraits of Photographers, 1982-2007. II. San Francisco Community Photographs, circa 1981-2009. III. Scenes from the American West, 1982-2008. IV. Portraits Acquired in 2012, 1983-1984. V. Portraits and Views Acquired in 2017, 1982-2017.

Occassionally a title applied by Aronow to a photograph involves word play or a purposeful misspelling related to the image content.

scopecontent.head: Scope and Contents
scopecontent.p: Photographs that chiefly consists of portraits of individuals involved in the arts, letters, and sciences with images created between 1982 and 2012 and printed between 2002 and 2017. Many of the portrait subjects relate to the American West. A small group of views primarily document sites related to water use in the American West.

arrangement.head: Arrangement
